And so Jesus gives them two parables in response to the questions that they asked.

01:16.515 --> 01:23.624
And the question that they posed to him was, who gave you Jesus such great authority to do all these things?

01:24.184 --> 01:28.970
And they were referring to the teachings, the miracles and the healings, everything he had been doing up to that point.

01:29.871 --> 01:32.114
As Jesus often does, I love this,

01:32.290 --> 01:38.439
He first responds to their question with a question of his own when he asks them in verse 25.

01:39.921 --> 01:45.829
Did John the Baptist's authority to baptize come from heaven or was it merely human?

01:46.911 --> 01:58.227
Next, we read that Jesus clearly catches them in a bind with how to respond to the point that after mowing together about the question, they respond by saying, we don't know.

01:59.909 --> 02:00.530
Jesus

02:00.706 --> 02:07.775
always the best opportunist sees a valuable moment to capitalize on the opportunity to deliver two parables here.

02:08.576 --> 02:12.741
Now remember, Jesus was a master storyteller and communicator, right?

02:12.822 --> 02:19.490
Which means he always spoke appropriately to whomever his listening audience might have been.

02:19.510 --> 02:28.722
Additionally, I always love the fact that many times Jesus gives multiple parables back to back that usually tie into one another or

02:28.834 --> 02:32.138
speak on the same theme, but from a different perspective.

02:32.298 --> 02:40.148
So in other words, all right, if I explained you how to do something one way and you don't quite get it, I'm going to try to explain it to you a different way and hopefully that will stick.

02:41.309 --> 02:45.514
In today's passage, Jesus gives it to us straight in both parables.

02:45.574 --> 02:46.155
He really does.

02:46.816 --> 02:58.450
Earlier in his ministry in his teaching in the Gospels, Christ may have taught the parable and then left it up to interpretation a little bit or left it up to understanding by those whose

02:58.690 --> 03:10.902
hearts and minds were prepared to read between the lines of his storytelling in order to see the deeper message and the deeper implications of his teachings.

03:10.922 --> 03:20.491
Now, here we see Christ in Jerusalem at the peak of his ministry and active teachings, only three chapters away from his arrest.

03:21.812 --> 03:28.338
He is not leaving anything up for interpretation or confusion, both for his disciples and his listening audience.

03:28.610 --> 03:57.458
he wants to be blunt and clear as to who and what he is talking about and and we see that today first in the parable of the two sons and secondly in the parable of the evil farmers now these parables are referenced as much as some of the other parables are you know parable the prodigal son uh... the mustard seed you know you name it there's a bunch of other ones that are more highly referenced uh... just from a

03:57.922 --> 04:16.542
Quantitative standpoint quantitative standpoint right here these two the parable of the two sons and the parable the evil farmers I don't I personally haven't heard them preached on that much or used in teachings or references, you know, and so The first one the parable of the two sons.

04:16.602 --> 04:24.530
I'll just summarize it for us today, but a Man has two sons tells the older boy go out and work in the vineyard

04:24.610 --> 04:27.573
The son said, no, I won't go, but later changes his mind.

04:27.693 --> 04:30.075
And he does actually go anyway and does the work.

04:30.556 --> 04:33.859
Then the father tells the other younger son, no, you go and work.

04:34.319 --> 04:37.663
And he said, yes, sir, I will, but he never actually did.

04:37.703 --> 04:39.344
So he just lied about it.

04:39.384 --> 04:40.906
He just said he would do it, but he didn't do it.

04:41.166 --> 04:44.529
He said he was going to live one way, but he was actually living a different way.

04:45.550 --> 04:47.592
And so Jesus goes on to explain that.

04:47.913 --> 04:53.298
And he asked the leaders who were listening, which of the two obeyed his father to which they

04:53.474 --> 05:00.084
correctly replied, the first one, the one who said, no, I don't want to do it, I'm not going to, but then he went and did it anyways, right?

05:01.086 --> 05:12.403
And so he goes on to explain this, listen to what Jesus says, I tell you the truth, corrupt tax collectors and prostitutes will get into the kingdom of God before you do, speaking to the Pharisees here.

05:12.943 --> 05:22.578
For John the Baptist came and showed you the right way to live, but you didn't believe him while tax collectors and prostitutes did, and even when you saw this happening,

05:22.658 --> 05:26.764
you refuse to believe him and repent of your sins.

05:27.585 --> 05:32.433
Nothing to, no splitting hairs there, right from Jesus.

05:32.473 --> 05:38.101
So very direct, straightforward in the face of the Pharisees and religious leaders of the time.

05:39.043 --> 05:44.471
Now, I do want to read aloud the parable of the evil farmers for us before we discuss it.

05:44.872 --> 05:51.762
So here is Matthew chapter 21, starting with verse 33,

05:51.970 --> 05:54.053
going through the end of the chapter.

05:55.615 --> 05:57.077
Now listen to another story.

05:57.678 --> 06:05.709
A certain landowner planted a vineyard, built a wall around it, dug a pit for pressing out the grape juice, and built a lookout tower.

06:06.290 --> 06:10.856
Then he leased the vineyard to tenant farmers and moved to another country.

06:11.897 --> 06:16.523
At the time of the grape harvest, he sent his servants to collect his share of the crop.

06:16.924 --> 06:21.330
But the farmers grabbed his servants, beat one, killed one, and stoned the other.

06:21.666 --> 06:29.277
So the land owner sent a larger group of his servants to collect what was rightfully his, but the results were the same.

06:30.439 --> 06:36.568
Finally, the owner sent his very own son, thinking, surely they will respect my son.

06:37.209 --> 06:43.258
But when the tenant farmer saw his son coming, they said to one another, here comes the heir to this estate.

06:43.599 --> 06:47.204
Come on, let's kill him and get the estate for ourselves.

06:47.705 --> 06:51.250
So they grabbed him, dragged him out of the vineyard and murdered him.

06:51.906 --> 06:57.694
When the owner of the vineyard returns, Jesus asked, what do you think he will do to those farmers?"

06:58.555 --> 06:59.997
The religious leaders replied.

07:01.239 --> 07:08.148
He will put the wicked men to a horrible death and lease the vineyard to others who will give him his share of the crop after each harvest.

07:09.070 --> 07:13.796
Then Jesus asked them, didn't you ever read this in the scriptures?

07:14.597 --> 07:18.162
The stone that the builders rejected has now become the cornerstone.

07:18.562 --> 07:21.987
This is the Lord's doing, and it is wonderful to see.

07:23.008 --> 07:28.536
I tell you, the kingdom of God will be taken away from you and given to a nation that will produce the proper fruit.

07:29.377 --> 07:35.485
Anyone who stumbles over that stone will be broken two pieces, and it will crush anyone it falls on.

07:36.807 --> 07:42.955
When the leading priest and Pharisees heard this parable, they realized he was telling the story against them.

07:43.016 --> 07:45.739
They were the wicked farmers.

07:46.480 --> 07:47.762
They wanted to arrest him,

07:47.874 --> 07:52.160
but they were afraid of the crowds who considered Jesus to be a prophet.

07:54.303 --> 08:01.312
Now a quick side note here, verse 42, where it talks about this is the stone that the builders rejected has now become the cornerstone.

08:01.673 --> 08:11.987
That is a direct quote from Psalm chapter 118, verse 22, which I strongly, strongly encourage you to go back and read it in its entirety.

08:12.387 --> 08:17.234
But while you're there, seriously, while you're there, read Psalm 119

08:17.666 --> 08:23.433
It's a little bit long, it's poetic, but it speaks on so many great things that I think anyone can relate to.

08:23.833 --> 08:28.459
It's like a really beautiful prayer conversation and plea from the author to God.

08:28.999 --> 08:35.587
When you read Psalm 119, let it be a prayer from you, the reader, to God when you get the chance.

08:36.688 --> 08:41.114
All right, now back to the point of Jesus's parable of the evil farmers.

08:42.375 --> 08:44.818
So here we have

08:45.026 --> 08:49.793
three different situations where the farmer sends someone to represent him for his estate.

08:50.674 --> 09:02.112
And the parallel here is that God has sent multiple prophets, multiple signs and examples of his love for the Israelite and Jewish people.

09:03.674 --> 09:11.666
But repeatedly we see throughout the Old Testament that the people turned away from God and either took up false idols, false religions,

09:11.810 --> 09:17.520
or just abandoned his teachings, or perverted the teachings in one way or another completely, right?

09:17.980 --> 09:28.037
I think about the Israelites when Moses was on the mountain, literally receiving command from God, and when he came back down, they had already abandoned what they knew and had made a false idol of that golden calf.

09:28.598 --> 09:35.570
And so, ultimately, the farm owner here in this situation sends his son, of course,

09:36.162 --> 09:40.367
Our representation here, the son of the farmer is the son of God.

09:40.427 --> 09:41.789
That is Jesus, right?

09:42.089 --> 09:45.093
And so he's saying, here I am, the Messiah and the flesh.

09:45.413 --> 09:46.895
I've done all these examples for you.

09:46.915 --> 09:48.056
I've done all these miracles for you.

09:48.076 --> 09:51.861
And yet you still don't believe you are here right now in the moment.

09:52.101 --> 09:53.863
You are seeing these miracles in real time.

09:54.243 --> 09:57.307
People in 2020, 26 won't have this ability.

09:57.327 --> 09:59.169
They'll have to read it and believe it through faith.

09:59.610 --> 10:03.154
You, the religious leaders of the law who know the Old Testament,

10:03.298 --> 10:08.886
have seen me in the flesh, the Messiah come to you, but you still are rejecting it?

10:09.647 --> 10:11.410
What more can I do, right?

10:11.710 --> 10:26.232
And so on that note, I think it's easy for all of us to imagine how the Pharisees were feeling after hearing this parable from Jesus and realizing that they were the real life representation of the fictional evil farmers.

10:26.993 --> 10:30.258
They had just been called out directly and in public.

10:31.042 --> 10:47.541
I'm certain there were some of the Pharisees, maybe the majority of them, who were simply outraged by this, and refused to use it as a moment of inward reflection, and instead use it as further fuel to the fire behind getting this Jesus guy arrested, or better yet, let's get him killed.

10:48.422 --> 10:58.194
Then again, I'd like to imagine that there were death certainly some of the other Pharisees listening that day, who were maybe on the verge or were

10:58.274 --> 11:04.382
sort of hearing the words of Jesus and were maybe in a situation of their heart being convicted, right?

11:04.882 --> 11:14.755
And so I imagine there were some who did feel convicted and had to seriously take a step back to look at how they were living their lives and ask themselves if that is what they really wanted.

11:15.135 --> 11:20.702
Were they being genuine with themselves or were they living a false life of holiness?

11:22.104 --> 11:23.666
Maybe they were thinking

11:23.810 --> 11:40.328
If this Jesus is truly who he says he is, and if his teachings are true and from God, then I'm only fooling myself by living in the delusion that as long as I look holy to the outside world, as long as I check all these boxes, then I've got it all figured out.

11:42.210 --> 11:49.938
To us listening or studying Jesus' words today, we should not just gloss over this parable, or think of it as something that

11:50.018 --> 11:56.806
doesn't pertain to us specifically because, well, we aren't Pharisees, we aren't ancient Jewish teachers of the law, we aren't Jewish, right?

11:57.487 --> 12:09.662
It's easy to put ourselves in the camp of Jesus and his disciples and to not side with the Pharisees in these moments because we often view them as the bad guys of the Gospels, right?

12:10.002 --> 12:19.474
And though that may be largely true to a point, the thing that I want us to be aware of is that it's maybe easier than we think for each of us

12:19.714 --> 12:26.742
to slip into a similar way of thinking or a similar way of living like the Pharisees.

12:28.404 --> 12:33.330
Will we condemn Christ to the cross if he showed up right here in 2026?

12:34.231 --> 12:34.892
Certainly not.

12:35.352 --> 12:47.186
But how often are we too quick to assume someone or some other group as maybe guilty or sinful or not right with God before

12:47.298 --> 12:52.765
taking the time to learn the full details or before getting to know the full person.

12:54.087 --> 12:57.691
Would we mock Christ or spit in his face either literally or figuratively?

12:58.152 --> 12:58.893
Of course not.

12:59.293 --> 13:15.794
But how often are we too quick to mock or slander or speak down on someone or a whole group of people because they have different lifestyles than us, different political opinions, or maybe they've experienced life in the love of God differently than us?

13:17.442 --> 13:40.008
I think it is important for us to realize over time if we aren't careful we can shift from clearly being in Jesus's camp into maybe either by accident or without noticing it being more in line with the camp of the religious leaders and Pharisees that Jesus was often butting up against during his ministry.

13:40.989 --> 13:45.554
And this happens when we start to put our own agenda or church agenda

13:45.666 --> 13:50.051
ahead of what God's true agenda and goal is, right?

13:50.792 --> 14:10.774
That's why we need people with different spiritual gifts to be a part of the body of Christ so that we can check each other during along the way, lean into each other's strengths and weaknesses and to make sure that we are functioning as one cohesive church body but made up of many different high functioning individual parts.

14:11.975 --> 14:14.578
We slide into this other camp of thinking

14:14.914 --> 14:32.192
when we make a choice to act on or implement policies fueled from our own personal opinions before taking the step to bounce what we want off of scripture and first asking, is this really God's will or is this just my will?

14:32.973 --> 14:38.438
Does this serve the whole church's purpose or does it mainly just serve my purpose?

14:40.180 --> 14:42.162
Typically I like to leave any

14:42.242 --> 14:47.669
message teaching or podcast off on a positive note, maybe even like a call to action in some way.

14:47.689 --> 15:01.828
But I think for today's context, it is most helpful for all of us listening, myself included, to end with a general warning that can be gleaned from Christ's teachings that we see here in Matthew chapter 21.

15:03.971 --> 15:09.458
The first thing is don't fall into the trap of thinking that you've got it all figured out like the Pharisees did.

15:09.762 --> 15:14.912
Be careful to make sure that your heart and mind stays rooted in God's true scripture.

15:15.413 --> 15:28.678
It's easy for us over time if we don't come back and study it to forget those words of scripture or to twist scripture in our mind to work for our agenda or what our goals are or what our desires are in our life.

15:29.219 --> 15:32.946
The second thing, remember, none of us are perfect

15:33.250 --> 15:45.346
There is always deeper to grow and learn in our relationship with Christ and how we can then impact the people and places around us out of being in relation with Christ.

15:46.187 --> 15:52.095
Lastly, seek the counsel and guidance of the Holy Spirit daily.

15:52.375 --> 16:00.306
Seek it daily and make sure that you are being honest with yourself as to what your true character is.

16:02.498 --> 16:06.383
I hope this podcast reading has been a blessing to you as it has been to me.

16:06.403 --> 16:12.750
And remember, be grateful today and every day for all of us have something to be thankful for.

16:12.770 --> 16:23.383
Thank you for listening to this podcast focused around the book of Matthew, produced by the marvelous Kinney Stewart from the beautiful Perdido Bay Methodist Church.

16:23.403 --> 16:25.746
We hope you have a great day.

